  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.10751" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>
        <dateline>
          <placeName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.1">
Sare</placeName>, par <placeName
              ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.95">St. <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Jean</hi> de Luz</placeName>
          <lb/> 7 <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">juin</hi> 1894<lb/>
        </dateline>
        <opener>Dear Professor,</opener>
        <p>I have received this afternoon from <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.4157">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">The Academy</hi>
          </ref> a copy of <bibl>
            <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8110">Urte’s translation of Genesis</ref>
          </bibl> etc.<note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.8110">Thomas, Llewelyn (1894) <hi
                  rend="unknown" rendition="#none">The earliest Translation of the Old Testament into the Basque Language (a fragment) by Pierre d´Urte of St. Jean-de-Luz, circa 1700</hi>
              </ref>

            </bibl>. Oxford : Clarendon Press.</note>; und I expect that you will receive one in a day or two from <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.9">Oxford</placeName>. Advance copies are sent to reviews in <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.6083">England</placeName>. That is how I have mine earlier. I must write a few words on it in <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">The Academy</hi>, though I cannot pretend to criticise the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.languages#L.837">Basque</ref>. Many thanks for your letter. I have thought it my duty to write to Mr. <persName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2860">Llewellyn Thomas</persName> about D’s, threat of publishing private letters.<note
            n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName
              ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1402">
Dodgson</persName> hatte u.a. 1889 in der Zeitschrift <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.5799">
              <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Euskara</hi>
            </ref> Briefe von Schuchardt ohne dessen Zustimmung veröffentlicht.</note> I have long creased to correspond with him, and I am very sure that he will not publish the last two letters that I wrote to him. Nothing can justify his language to you about the religion of Jesus. His only excuse can be that he is not sane as other men are, in spite of his remarkable talent in formal language.</p>
        <p>Have you seen that at last Anthropologists are beginning to find that ‘Broca<note n="3" place="foot" type="editorial">
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.5502">Paul Broca</persName> ist, neben anderen neurologischen Studien, die wissenschaftlich von bleibender Bedeutung waren, auch anthropometrische Wege gegangen. So hat er z.B. auch Theorien über Schädelformen aufgestellt und u.a. Schädelmessungen bei den Basken unternommen: Broca, Paul (1868) <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.7721">
                <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Mémoire sur les Crances des Basques de Saint-Jean-de-Luz suivi de recherches sur la Comparaison des Indices Céphaliques sur le vivant et sur le squelette</hi>
              </ref>
            </bibl>. Paris: Victor Masson. Außerdem gibt es 1875 aus seiner Feder eine Arbeit über den Ursprung die die Verbreitung des Baskischen: <bibl>
              <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.bibliography#BIBL.5822">Sur l'origine er la répartition de la Langue Basque. Basques français et basques espagnols</ref>

            </bibl>. Paris: Leroux.</note> or the Basque Skull’ is not the trustworthy document that they had supposed. I wish you a happy festival at <placeName
            ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.places#PL.97">Viena</placeName>, and a pleasant meeting with <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2915">Don Juan Valera</persName>
          <note n="4" place="foot" type="editorial">Schuchardt hatte <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2915">Juan Valera</persName> auf seiner Spanienreise 1879 kennengelernt und mit ihm einen Briefwechsel unterhalten, der auch sehr herzliche Töne annimmt, HSA 12327-12334.</note>, whose admirer I am.</p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Kindest regards.<lb/> Yous very truly<lb/>
          </salute>
          <signed>
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
              <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.2983">
WW</persName>
            </hi>
          </signed>
        </closer>
      </div>
